JavaScript String Methods – Summary Notes

1. Changing Case

toLowerCase() – Converts string to lowercase.

toUpperCase() – Converts string to uppercase.

Use for input standardization.

Example:

const name = 'jOnAs';
const properName = name[0].toUpperCase() + name.slice(1).toLowerCase();

2. Trimming Whitespace

trim() – Removes whitespace from both ends.

trimStart(), trimEnd() – Remove only from start/end.

Example:

const email = '  Hello@Example.com  ';
const cleaned = email.trim().toLowerCase();

3. Replacing Text

replace(old, new) – Replaces first match.

replaceAll(old, new) – Replaces all matches.

Regex with /g can replace globally.

Example:

const price = '288,97£';
const usPrice = price.replace('£', '$').replace(',', '.');

4. Checking Substrings

includes(sub) – True if substring found.

startsWith(sub) – True if starts with substring.

endsWith(sub) – True if ends with substring.

Example:

const plane = 'Airbus A320neo';
plane.includes('A320');     // true
plane.startsWith('Airbus'); // true

5. Real-life Example: Security Check

Convert text to lowercase before checking.

Example:

function checkBaggage(items) {
  const baggage = items.toLowerCase();
  if (baggage.includes('knife') || baggage.includes('gun')) {
    console.log('Not allowed');
  } else {
    console.log('Allowed');
  }
}
